ls -- tCONCLUSION -- tLIST OF CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCritical Approaches to Science and Religion offers a new direction for scholarship on science and religion that examines social, political, and ecological concerns long part of the field but never properly centered. The works that make up this volume are not preoccupied with traditional philosophical or theological issues. Instead, the book draws on three vital schools of thought: critical race theory, feminist and queer theory, and postcolonial theory. Featuring a diverse array of contributors, it develops critical perspectives by examining how histories of empire, slavery, colonialism, and patriarchy have shaped the many relationships between science and religion in the modern era. In so doing, this book lays the groundwork for scholars interested in speaking directly to matters such as climate change, structural racism, immigration, health care, reproductive justice, and sexual identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aReligion and science. 7aRELIGION / Religion & Science.2bisacsh  aclimate change.  acritical race theory.  acritical theory.  afeminist theory.  ahealthcare.  aimmigration.  aphilosophy of religion.  apostcolonial theory.  aqueer theory.  areproductive justice.  ascience and religion.  asexual identity.  astructural racism.1 aAdcock, Cassie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrosson, J. Brent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerbner, Katharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraves, Joseph L Jr., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeel, Terence, econtributor.4ctb4https://